main event: On November 23, 1957, a GOC observer in Washington Island, Wisconsin reported a sighting of a round object that a jet aircraft could not catch up to. The object was larger than a star and possibly pink in color. The observation lasted for 5 minutes as the object moved northeast and eventually faded over the horizon.
interesting points: The round object was described as larger than a star and possibly pink in color.
The GOC observer reported that the object was moving northeast and eventually faded over the horizon in about two minutes.
The sighting lasted for 5 minutes, and the observer was a housewife aged 45, adding a specific detail about the witness.
There were no photographs taken of the sighting, and there was limited data available for evaluation.
The conclusion of the sighting was marked as 'Insufficient Data for Evaluation' by the report.
sighted object: Round object, possibly pink, larger than a star
witnesses: GOC observer, Mrs. C.B. Eaton, housewife aged 45
